{"finish_reason":"length","index":4,"logprobs":null,"message":{"content":"Key Points
                    - After rectal cancer has been diagnosed, tests are done to find out if cancer cells have spread within the rectum or to other parts of the body.     - There are three ways that cancer spreads in the body.    - Cancer may spread from where it began to other parts of the body.    - Rectal cancer may affect sexual and urinary function in men.     -  For men who have rectal cancer and are sexually active or may become sexually active, it is important to discuss the possible effects of treatment on sexual health with doctors and seek help for sexual problems.    - Rectal cancer may affect sexual and urinary function in women.     - For women who have rectal cancer and are sexually active or may become sexually active, it is important to discuss the possible effects of treatment on sexual health with doctors and seek help for sexual problems.     - Psychosexual counseling may help patients and their partners cope with sexual problems.         After rectal cancer has been diagnosed, tests are done to find out if cancer cells have spread within the rectum or to other parts of the body.


                    The process used to find out if cancer has spread within the rectum or to other parts of the body is called staging. The information gathered from the staging process determines the stage of the disease. The results of the tests and procedures used to diagnose rectal cancer are often also used to stage the disease. See the General Information section of this summary.    The following tests and procedures may be used in the staging process:         -   CT Colonography : A procedure to look inside the colon and rectum for polyps (abnormal growths) or other abnormalities using x-rays and computers. Pictures of the inside of the colon and rectum are made by a computer connected to an x-ray machine. This procedure is also called virtual colonoscopy, because the pictures create a very clear view, much like a colonoscopy.    -   ERUS  (endorectal ultrasound): An ultrasound procedure used to see inside the rectum and nearby organs. An endoscope is inserted into the rectum and sends out sound waves that bounce off tissues inside the body and make echoes. The echoes form a picture of any tumor that is present and nearby organs on a monitor. Also called transrectal ultrasound (TRUS).    -   Exploratory laparoscopy : A surgical procedure to look at the organs inside the abdomen to check for signs of disease. An incision (cut) is made in the wall of the abdomen and a laparoscope (thin, lighted tube) is inserted into the abdomen. Other small incisions may be made and special instruments may be used to move organs and tissues aside so the doctor can get a better view.    -   MRI  (magnetic resonance imaging): A procedure that uses a magnet, radio waves, and a computer to make a series of detailed pictures of areas inside the body. This procedure is also called nuclear magnetic resonance imaging (NMRI).    -   PET scan : A procedure to find malignant tumor cells in the body. A small amount of radioactive glucose (sugar) is injected into a vein. The PET scanner rotates around the body and makes a picture of where glucose is being used in the body. Malignant tumor cells show up brighter in the picture because they are more active and take up more glucose than normal cells. If there is any glucose uptake in the liver and at the site of the tumor, a biopsy is done to see if there are cancer cells.         The results of the tests and procedures used to diagnose rectal cancer are also used to stage the disease.    The following stages are used for rectal cancer:         -   Stage 0  (carcinoma in situ): The cancer is found only in the mucosa, or innermost layer of cells of the rectum.    -   Stage I : Cancer has formed in the mucosa and has spread into the wall of the rectum.     -   Stage II : Cancer has spread through the wall of the rectum.    -   Stage III : Cancer has spread through the wall of the rectum and to nearby lymph nodes.    -   Stage IV : Cancer has spread to other parts of the body such as the liver or lungs.          The following stages are used for recurrent rectal cancer:         -   Recurrent rectal cancer can occur in the pelvis (in the same place as the original tumor or near the original tumor) or in other parts of the body. This can be difficult to cure and may cause signs or symptoms. Treatment is used to help relieve these signs and symptoms and improve quality of life. The purpose of treatment is to try to totally remove the cancer if possible.      - For recurrent rectal cancer that occurs in other parts of the body, the cancer may spread to the lungs or, less often, to the liver, brain, bone, or other parts of the body","refusal":null,"role":"assistant","annotations":[],"audio":null,"function_call":null,"tool_calls":null}}

{"finish_reason":"stop","index":4,"logprobs":null,"message":{"content":"The body is made up of trillions of cells. Normally, cells grow and divide to form new cells as the body needs them. When cells grow old, they die, and new cells take their place. Sometimes this orderly process goes wrong. New cells form when the body does not need them, and old cells do not die when they should. These extra cells can divide without stopping and may spread into (invade) nearby tissue. In addition to invading nearby tissue, cancer cells can break away from a tumor and enter the bloodstream or lymphatic system. As they travel through the bloodstream or lymph system, they can settle in other parts of the body. This is called metastasis.     Bladder cancer forms in the tissues of the bladder and is named according to the tissue where the cancer forms. The most common type of bladder cancer, called transitional cell carcinoma, starts in cells called urothelial cells lining up inside the bladder. Transitions cells can also be found in the ureters and top part of the urethra (see below).    The bladder is a hollow organ in the lower part of the abdomen. It is about the size and shape of a pear. The bladder has an expandable wall made of layers of connective tissue and muscle lined by a thin, moist layer of tissue made of a special type of epithelial cells called transitional cells. The bladder stores urine, which is made by the kidneys and carried to the bladder by two thin tubes called ureters. When urine is formed, extra fluid and waste material are removed from the blood by the kidneys and become urine. Urine flows from the kidneys through the ureters and into the bladder. When the bladder becomes full, urine is passed through another tube called the urethra out of the body.     Although various factors increase the risk of getting bladder cancer, there is no sure way to prevent it.    Bladder cancer may cause no signs or symptoms in its early stages.    


    Key Points
    - Bladder cancer is a disease in which malignant (cancer) cells form in the tissues of the bladder.    - The most common type of bladder cancer starts in cells called urothelial cells that line the inside of the bladder.    - Bladder cancer may not cause signs or symptoms in its early stages.    - Having blood in the urine is a common sign of bladder cancer.    - Tests that examine the urine and bladder are used to detect (find) and diagnose bladder cancer.    - Some factors affect treatment options and prognosis (chance of recovery).    - Cancer treatment can cause side effects.    - Five types of standard treatment are used:         - Surgery      - Intravesical therapy      - Chemotherapy      - Radiation therapy      - Immunotherapy        - New types of treatment are being tested in clinical trials.    - Patients may want to think about taking part in a clinical trial.    - Follow-up tests may be needed.        Bladder cancer is a disease in which malignant (cancer) cells form in the tissues of the bladder.","refusal":null,"role":"assistant","annotations":[],"audio":null,"function_call":null,"tool_calls":null}}

{"finish_reason":"stop","index":3,"logprobs":null,"message":{"content":"Summary : Marijuana is the dried leaves, stems, flower buds, and resin from the Cannabis sativa or Cannabis indica plant. The plant contains the mind-altering chemical THC and other similar compounds. Some people take marijuana to get high. Others feel that it helps them relax, feel less anxious, and in some cases, feel less nauseated and more hungry.

Usually, marijuana is smoked as a cigarette (called a joint), in a small pipe, or in a water pipe (sometimes called a bong). People also smoke it in blunts, which are hollowed-out cigars. In addition, marijuana leaves can be mixed with food, or the main active chemical can be extracted and made into a medicine.

When a person uses marijuana, the brain is affected almost immediately. The person starts to feel high, or "stoned." This feeling includes a heightened sensory perception. For example, colors might seem brighter and sounds might seem sharper. Portions of Scripture or of a song might take on unusual meaning. Time seems to slow down. Tasks become funny, so the user laughs more.      The high varies from person to person and depends on the situation, such as who the user is with and where the user is. The effect of the drug depends on how much is taken and also on the user's personality and mood. If enough THC is taken, the user might also feel anxious or nervous, or have a feeling of panic.      Continued use of marijuana may lead to psychological addiction.    NIH: National Institute on Drug Abuse","refusal":null,"role":"assistant","annotations":[],"audio":null,"function_call":null,"tool_calls":null}}
